pan><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?_</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">mpr</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">?_</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">normSq_nonneg</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">I</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">simp</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">rw</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Complex</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">normSq_apply</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">-</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">I</span><span class=\"o\">)]</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>and I get stuck. Potentially, I could try and rewrite .re and .im, but they have a type C -&gt; R, so that doesn't work, not to mention having to prove 1 : Real = Real.ofCauchy (sorry /- 1, 1, ... -/). Is the whole statement wrong due to type issues and, if so, how should I fix it?</p>",
